  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <div class="page-content">
        <p>A high school sports banquet is more than just dinner and awards. It's the night a team's season comes full circle. It's where athletes feel recognized, coaches express their appreciation, and families see the impact of the program.</p>
        <p>Planning an event that lives up to that weight can feel overwhelming. This guide breaks it down into manageable steps so you can focus on what matters — celebrating your athletes.</p>

        <h2>The 8-Week Planning Timeline</h2>

        <h3>Week 8-6: Foundation</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Set date and secure venue</strong> — Popular venues book weeks in advance. Start early.</li>
          <li><strong>Establish budget</strong> — The average high school sports banquet costs $15-35 per person.</li>
          <li><strong>Form planning committee</strong> — Coach, booster rep, and 2-3 parent volunteers.</li>
          <li><strong>Decide program format</strong> — Dinner-first or awards-first? Each has its advantages.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Week 5-4: Logistics</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Send save-the-dates and invitations</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Order decorations and centerpieces</strong> — Custom 3D printed items require 2-3 weeks lead time</li>
          <li><strong>Plan menu with venue or caterer</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Prepare award certificates and trophies</strong></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Week 3-2: Final Details</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Confirm RSVPs</strong> — Finalize headcount for catering</li>
          <li><strong>Assign seating</strong> — Pro tip: mix underclassmen with seniors</li>
          <li><strong>Rehearse program flow</strong> — Speaker order, timing, transitions</li>
          <li><strong>Set up photo area</strong> — Including backdrop and good lighting</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Choosing the Right Venue</h2>
        <p>The venue sets the tone for your entire banquet. Popular options include school gymnasiums or cafeterias (budget-friendly), local banquet halls, restaurants with private rooms, community centers, and churches or civic buildings. Consider capacity, parking, AV equipment availability, and whether you can bring your own decorations and centerpieces.</p>

        <h2>Menu Planning for Athletes & Families</h2>
        <p>Athletes have big appetites but also varied dietary needs. A buffet or family-style service works best for large groups. Popular menu options include pasta bars, BBQ, taco bars, and classic catered dinners. Don't forget vegetarian, gluten-free, and allergy-friendly options.</p>

        <h2>Centerpiece Ideas for Sports Banquets</h2>
        <p>Table centerpieces are one of the most visible elements of your banquet. They set the tone, create photo-worthy moments, and become a talking point for weeks.</p>
        <p>Custom 3D printed sports centerpieces have become increasingly popular because they capture team identity in a way generic centerpieces can't. Each piece is designed for your specific sport — football helmets, basketball hoops, baseball diamonds, soccer nets, volleyballs, and more — crafted in your team's colors.</p>

